      'As we covered in our article on [how to manage tantrums practically](/blog/como-gestionar-rabietas-regulacion-emocional-ninos), young children (between 2 and 4 years old) have tantrums because their prefrontal cortex — the part of the brain that controls impulses — is still immature.',
      'However, if your child is 6, 8 or 10 years old and still has uncontrollable anger explosions, breaks things or takes hours to calm down, the tantrum is a symptom that there\'s something more. Often, behind an "angry and aggressive" child there\'s a deeply anxious child, one who is suffering bullying, or who has [undiagnosed neurodivergence](/blog/tdah-tea-diagnostico-terapia-ninos) (such as ADHD or [Giftedness](/blog/altas-capacidades-intelectuales-evaluacion-ninos)).',
